---
import SiteLayout from '../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

const description =
	'About Chad: a full-stack distributed-systems engineer building high-throughput BEAM platforms with Elixir, Phoenix, Postgres, Redis, and Riak.';
---

<SiteLayout title="About" description={description} active="about" promptPath="about">
	<section class="reading-shell about" aria-labelledby="about-heading">
		<div class="identity">
			<p class="ds-overline">$ whoami</p>
			<h1 id="about-heading">I build systems that have to stay up.</h1>
		</div>

		<div class="prose">
			<p>
				I'm Chad, a full-stack distributed-systems engineer specializing in
				high-throughput platforms on the BEAM. I work primarily in Elixir, and I'm most
				at home where scale meets reliability: the systems that have to stay fast and
				stay up as traffic keeps climbing.
			</p>
			<p>
				At Blitz, I helped scale Elixir/Phoenix GraphQL services to around 18k requests
				per second at 99.99% uptime, built ETL pipelines that ingest 2k events per
				second into Postgres, Redis, and Riak, and sustained 40k durable writes per
				second on Postgres while reducing the instance footprint.
			</p>
			<p>
				That kind of work is where architecture stops being a diagram and starts being
				pressure: throughput, operability, cost, failure modes, team coordination, and
				the boring interfaces that decide whether a system can keep changing.
			</p>
			<p>
				I believe that with good process and the right people, you can build anything.
				This blog is where I share what I've learned along the way: architecture
				decisions, tradeoffs, and the hard-won lessons of running real systems at scale.
			</p>
		</div>
	</section>
</SiteLayout>

<style>
	.about {
		display: grid;
		gap: var(--space-7);
	}

	.identity {
		display: grid;
		gap: var(--space-3);
	}

	.identity p {
		color: var(--accent);
		margin: 0;
	}

	h1 {
		color: var(--text);
		font-family: var(--font-display);
		font-size: var(--text-h1);
		line-height: var(--leading-tight);
		margin: 0;
		overflow-wrap: anywhere;
	}
</style>
